= Research Statement

Research in economics often focuses on quantifiable markets and policy impacts, yet the narratives spun around these economics dimensions also shape societal behavior profoundly. My work investigates how entertainment media such as telenovelas serve not only as mirrors of cultural norms but also as agents fostering social and economic change. By transforming unstructured narrative content into structured econometric data through novel applications of generative artificial intelligence, my approach enables rigorous empirical study of culture’s influence on economics within a high-frequency and scalable framework.

The focus on Latin American telenovelas leverages their cultural significance to empirically identify causal pathways by which media narratives affect female labor force participation and preferences for socioeconomic redistribution. My job market paper, “Does Watching Women Work, Work? The Effect of Television on Female Labor Outcomes,” introduces a Female Empowerment Index that synthesizes AI-driven content analysis with econometric instruments exploiting quasi-random variation in television reception in Mexico. This research demonstrates that exposure to empowering portrayals of women in the labor market can materially influence female employment patterns, offering insights with broader relevance to gender equity and labor economics.

Complementing this, my second paper examines how telenovelas depicting social class inequality impact attitudes towards redistribution. Employing cutting-edge natural language processing methods, including zero-shot classification via generative AI, this work reveals that portrayals of inequality may paradoxically diminish support for redistributive policies when narratives misrepresent marginalized groups. This finding underscores the nuanced ways cultural narratives intersect with economic preferences and political economy.

Colorado College’s commitment to immersive liberal arts education and fostering an inclusive, diverse learning community aligns closely with my research’s foundational themes of culture and equity. The innovative Block Plan structure offers an exceptional environment for engaging students deeply in project-based learning, particularly through opportunities for undergraduates to contribute to data collection and validation of AI models. This hands-on involvement matches my experience mentoring research assistants and my dedication to integrating research and teaching.

Though my primary research has focused on cultural economics and gender, the methodological tools I develop and the substantive themes addressed have strong connections to macroeconomics and international economics, especially regarding labor market dynamics and social preferences that influence economic policy and outcomes globally. I am eager to extend my research agenda to incorporate broader economic phenomena relevant to the department’s macroeconomic specialization, including the role of political economy and media producers’ decisions in shaping narratives that affect economic behavior.

Moreover, my work’s interdisciplinary nature and use of innovative AI technology offers a unique contribution to Colorado College’s curriculum, particularly in international finance, money and banking, and macroeconomics courses. I am committed to maintaining a vigorous research agenda alongside my teaching responsibilities and contributing actively to the General Education program and departmental service.

In sum, my research merges advanced empirical methodology with pressing themes of equity and cultural influence, resonating with Colorado College’s values and its distinctive educational philosophy. This alignment provides a strong foundation for collaborative scholarship and innovative pedagogy within the economics department and the broader college community.
